	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>EC proposes January 2014 as deadline for completion of EPA process</h1>

			
			<h4>
												20 October 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>On 30 September 2011 the European Commission adopted a proposal ‘to amend the Market Access Regulation … 1528/2007’, which provides transitional duty-free access to ACP countries whose governments have initialled an interim EPA. This proposal calls on the EU Council and the European Parliament to empower the European Commission to ‘amend the list of countries that benefit from the preferences (Annex I of Council Regulation (EC) No 1528/2007) by removing those which have still not taken the necessary steps towards ratification of an EPA’. It calls on the Council and Parliament to delegate powers to the EC to reinstate countries on the list where the governments concerned ‘have since taken the necessary steps towards ratification of their respective agreements after removal from Annex I’.</p><p>According to an EC information note, ‘Eighteen countries (14 countries in the Caribbean, Madagascar, Mauritius, Seychelles and Papua New Guinea) have taken the necessary steps towards ratification of initialled agreements, and will continue to use the facility’, while 18 other countries ‘have not even signed their agreement or are still not applying it’.</p><a name="eztoc488335_0_0_0_0_1" id="eztoc488335_0_0_0_0_1"></a><h6>Table: Status of countries’ EPA commitments</h6><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
<td width="295" valign="top">  <b>Countries whose governments have initialled but not signed an (I)EPA</b>
  </td><td width="295" valign="top">  <b>Countries whose governments have signed but not taken steps to ratify their (I)EPA</b>
  </td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td width="295" valign="top">  <p><b>East African Community Customs Union </b></p>
<ul>

<li>Burundi</li>

<li>Kenya </li>

<li>Rwanda</li>

<li>Tanzania</li>

<li>Uganda</li>

</ul>
<p><b>Other ESA configuration</b></p>
<ul>

<li>Comoros</li>

<li>Zambia</li>

</ul>
<p><b>SADC EPA configuration</b></p>
<ul>

<li>Namibia</li>

</ul>
<p><b>West Africa EPA configuration </b></p>
<ul>

<li>Ghana</li>

</ul>

  </td><td width="295" valign="top">  <p><b>ESA EPA configuration</b></p>
<ul>

<li>Zimbabwe</li>

</ul>
<p><b>SADC EPA configuration</b></p>
<ul>

<li>Botswana</li>

<li>Lesotho</li>

<li>Swaziland</li>

<li>Mozambique;</li>

</ul>
<p><b>Central Africa EPA configuration </b></p>
<ul>

<li>Cameroon</li>

</ul>
<p><b>West Africa EPA configuration </b></p>
<ul>

<li>Côte d’Ivoire</li>

</ul>
<p><b>Pacific configuration</b></p>
<ul>

<li>Fiji</li>

</ul>
<p><b>Caribbean configuration</b></p>
<ul>

<li>Haiti</li>

</ul>

  </td>
</tr>

</table>
<p>Source: Extracted by author from EC proposal for regulation COM(2011) 598 final</p><p>For these 18 countries, the current duty-free, quota-free access enjoyed could be lost from 1 January 2014 under the proposal. The EC maintains that ‘the 18 countries which would be withdrawn from the Market Access Regulation have a choice: whether to go ahead and establish a partnership with the EU or not.’ This would require governments in these countries to ‘take the necessary steps towards ratification of existing Economic Partnership Agreements or conclude new regional Agreements with the EU’. The EC argues that recent developments should allow the countries concerned to ‘conclude ongoing regional negotiations in time’.</p><p>According to the EC information note, LDCs which do not sign an EPA will continue to benefit from the duty-free, quota-free access granted under the ‘Everything but arms’ (EBA) scheme. Seven ‘low-income or lower middle income countries (Cameroon, Fiji, Ghana, Ivory Coast, Kenya, Swaziland, Zimbabwe)’, would revert to GSP treatment, while two upper-middle income countries, Botswana and Namibia, ‘would not qualify for preferential access under the proposed revision to the Generalised System of Preferences’.</p><p>Significantly, the EC information note observes that since the measures proposed would come into effect on 1 January 2014, governments of potentially affected countries have ‘time to implement an Economic Partnership Agreement and thus maintain their current free access to the EU’.</p><p>The proposal will now go the EU Council and European Parliament for discussion and eventual adoption.</p><p>A blog posting published by ECDPM analysing and reviewing the EU proposal notes that the removal of duty-free, quota-free access would coincide with the implementation of the new EU GSP regulation, which reduced the number of ACP countries that would otherwise benefit from GSP preferences. It concludes that ‘the message is therefore clear: if countries want to continue to benefit from EPA market access, either they have to sign and start implementing their existing EPA or conclude a new regional EPA.’ It notes a range of substantive issues that still need to be addressed in the ongoing negotiations, including the accompanying development measures and the compatibility of certain EPA commitments with regional integration processes. Against this background, ECDPM concludes that ‘while a deadline by 1st January 2014 might seem a reasonable time … it is in fact very short for the proper sequencing of regional agenda with trade negotiations with third countries.’ It also suggests that the EC will need to show ‘how far it would be willing to accommodate some genuine concerns that are blocking the negotiations’. It is argued that ‘setting a deadline is …. not sufficient, the EU should come up with concrete proposals on how to move the negotiations forward.’ It suggests that ‘if no common position can be found at the regional level, the EPAs could seriously disrupt any regional integration effort.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>EC, ‘Access to EU markets for exporters from ACP countries’, 30 September 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.bilaterals.org/spip.php?article20344&amp;lang=en" target="_self">http://www.bilaterals.org/spip.php?article20344&amp;lang=en</a></p><p>ECDPM, ‘EPA negotiations: The honeymoon is over…’, blog post, <i>Talking Points</i>,<i>&nbsp;</i>30 September 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.ecdpm-talkingpoints.org/epa-negotiations-the-honeymoon-is-over/" target="_self">http://www.ecdpm-talkingpoints.org/epa-negotiations-the-honeymoon-is-over/</a></p><p>EC, point of access to‘Proposal for a regulation of the European Parliament and of the Council amending Annex I to Council Regulation (EC) No 1528/2007 as regards the exclusion of a number of countries from the list of regions or states which have concluded negotiations’, COM/2011/0598, 30 September 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.ipex.eu/IPEXL-WEB/dossier/dossier.do?code=COD&amp;year=2011&amp;number=0260" target="_self">http://www.ipex.eu/IPEXL-WEB/dossier/dossier.do?code=COD&amp;year=2011&a...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Two options appear to be open to ACP governments if duty-free, quota-free access is to be maintained: sign and ratify existing bilateral EPAs (or regional EPAs, in the case of the EAC countries), or negotiate, sign and ratify new comprehensive regional EPAs.</p><p>Since the EC proposed regulation makes reference to the November/December 2007 initialled texts and no reference to subsequent, often substantive ‘clarification’ negotiations, it is unclear what the outcome will be on a range of ‘contentious issues’.</p><p>Many of these ‘contentious issues’ have a bearing on the use of agricultural trade policy tools in ACP countries (see <i>Agritrade</i> special report ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Resources/Agritrade-documents/Special-reports/Contentious-issues-in-IEPA-negotiations-implications-and-questions-in-the-agricultural-sector" target="_blank">Contentious issues in IEPA negotiations: Implications and questions in t...</a>’, October 2008). The effectiveness of the use of these policy tools varies considerably from country to country and is closely linked to regionally specific circumstances. Thus in the SADC EPA context the current text, to which the Namibian government has consistently expressed objections, requires the immediate elimination of all restrictions on imports (including import and export licensing arrangements) upon entry into force of the agreement. Yet the use of import and export licences is an important market management tool in Namibia, and has been used successfully as part of wider sector policy frameworks to promote the development of agricultural production and value-added processing in the horticulture, cereals, livestock and dairy sectors (linked in some instances to infant industry protection provisions of the Southern African Customs Union agreement).</p><p>Elsewhere in Africa, for example in the EAC, there are growing private sector complaints about the arbitrary use of import and export licences in ways that disrupt both regional trade and investments in the development of production (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Cereals/Debate-on-the-use-of-national-export-bans-in-East-Africa" target="_blank">Debate on the use of national export bans in East Africa</a>’, October 2011).</p><p>Across the ACP the debate over the use of these tools has been thrown into sharp focus by rising food prices and heightened price volatility.</p><p>The critical issue in the EPA context is to judge the use of these policy tools on their merits in the individual national and regional circumstances which prevail.</p><p>The debate on these ‘contentious issues’ needs to be seen in a context where the EU makes extensive use of similar policy tools (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Topics/WTO/Agricultural-dimensions-of-the-WTO-EU-trade-policy-review" target="_blank">Agricultural dimensions of the WTO EU trade policy review</a>’, September 2011).</p><p>The foregoing example is merely illustrative of an important range of issues that still need to be addressed in the ongoing process of EPA negotiations. While progress has periodically been made towards pragmatically resolving these ‘contentious issues’ in the light of regional specificities and emerging global trends, agreed texts have not yet been formally integrated into the draft (I)EPAs initialled in November/December 2007. This raises the question: how will these outstanding contentious issues be dealt with in the coming 15 months?</p><p>This is potentially important, since the EC information note suggests that in order to determine the progress made after 1 January 2014, when the existing duty-free, quota-free access under the December 2007 regulation (no. 1528/2007) lapses, the EC will be looking at how countries are implementing EPA commitments.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

